    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>On Military Spending</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Tom Webb letter praises Oct 3 article about efforts of peace organizations to raise questions about US military spending</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your Oct. 3 news article about the efforts of peace organizations like Pax Christi USA and the Fellowship of Reconciliation to raise questions about military spending was timely.</p>
        <p>We have not had a substantial national debate that seriously questions assumptions behind military spending in light of our post-cold-war world. True, the Pentagon has declared its strategies and needs, but are they really our national needs?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your Oct. 3 news article about the efforts of peace organizations like Pax Christi USA and the Fellowship of Reconciliation to raise questions about military spending was timely.</p>
        <p>We have not had a substantial national debate that seriously questions assumptions behind military spending in light of our post-cold-war world. True, the Pentagon has declared its strategies and needs, but are they really our national needs?</p>
        <p>I hope this question will become a topic in the remaining weeks of our election season.</p>
        <p>TOM WEBB  Los Angeles, Oct. 3, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
